  <!-- ========== FAQ ========== -->
  <section class="section faq-section" id="faq" style="background: var(--bg-alt);" aria-label="Frequently asked questions about marketing for interior designers in Singapore">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header reveal">
        <p class="section-label">FAQ</p>
        <h2><span class="highlight">Interior Designer</span> Marketing — Questions <span class="highlight">Answered</span></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <details class="faq-item reveal reveal-d1">
          <summary>How much does marketing cost for an interior designer in Singapore?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer"><p>Interior designer marketing in Singapore starts at S$3,000 per month for essential single-channel work (typically SEO or social media). Growth packages at S$5,500/month combine SEO, Google Ads, and IG/TikTok with lead tracking. Enterprise packages at S$10,000+/month add video production, brand refresh, and a dedicated strategist. Renovation firms with multiple branches or premium positioning typically need the Growth tier minimum to compete with Qanvast and Renonation aggregator listings.</p></div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item reveal reveal-d2">
          <summary>Why can't I just rely on Qanvast and Renonation for leads?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer"><p>Aggregator platforms like Qanvast and Renonation send high-volume but low-margin leads — homeowners are typically comparing 5-8 firms simultaneously, and you pay per lead or per quote. Direct-to-firm marketing (SEO, Google Ads, IG, TikTok) builds a brand that homeowners search for by name, reducing lead cost over time and capturing higher-value clients who skip aggregator shortlists entirely.</p></div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item reveal reveal-d3">
          <summary>What's the buyer journey for an HDB or condo renovation in Singapore?</summary>
